# ✅ Scenario We’ll Build

**Goal:**

*   React app fetches data from an API (`/api/users`)
*   Service Worker caches the API response
*   When you:
    *   go **offline**, OR
    *   open the app in a **new tab**
*   👉 You still see the **same data**

***

# ✅ How It Works (High Level)

    React App → fetch("/api/users")
                       ↓
                Service Worker
                       ↓
            Cache API response (dynamic)
                       ↓
         Return cached data (offline / new tab)

***

# ✅ Step 1: React Component (Fetch Data)

📄 **`src/App.js`**

```jsx
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

function App() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("/api/users")
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setUsers(data))
      .catch(() => {
        console.log("Offline: using cached data");
      });
  }, []);

  return (
    <div style={{ padding: 20 }}>
      <h2>Users</h2>

      {users.map(user => (
        <p key={user.id}>{user.name}</p>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

✅ React code is **normal**  
✅ No caching logic in React  
✅ Service Worker handles everything

***

# ✅ Step 2: Register the Service Worker

📄 **`src/index.js`**

```js
if ("serviceWorker" in navigator) {
  window.addEventListener("load", () => {
    navigator.serviceWorker.register("/sw.js");
  });
}
```

✅ Runs once  
✅ Enables PWA behavior

